[2] Sri Lanka
Date: Sat 3 Jul 2004
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Daily News, Sri Lanka, 3 Jul 2003 [edited]
<http://www.dailynews.lk/2004/07/03/new10.html>

Dengue in Sri Lanka: 28 deaths & 6742 suspected cases
-----------------------------------------------
Health authorities yesterday [Fri 2 Jul 2004] warned that the dengue
epidemic could hit a peak in Jul 2004 owing to the poor response from
the public towards the dengue eradication program, including keeping
the environment clean.
The total number of suspected cases stood at 6743 by Fri 2 Jul 2004,
while the number of deaths due to dengue fever rose to 28. Gampaha
and Colombo districts are the worst affected, while Kurunegala,
Kandy, Trincomalee and Kalutara also recorded a high prevalence. Out
of the 48 deaths, 16 have been reported from Colombo [the capital].
In June 2004 alone, 190 cases had been reported within the Colombo
Municipality area, while the total number of cases stood at 430. 6
cases have been reported within the last 2 days of this month [July
2004], recording an alarming increase. A senior Health Ministry
official said the number of cases is increasing daily due to the rain
in many parts of the country. The highest number of dengue cases are
reported during June and July every year. "During this period, people
should be extra careful," Dr. Kariyawasam added. "Unless the public
supports [the cause] to ensure a clean environment, this might turn
into an epidemic causing a severe crisis," the official added. The
Health Ministry has urged the public to clear breeding places of
dengue mosquitoes by getting rid of cans, tins, coconut shells, old
tires, small containers, and roof gutters where rainwater collects.
"The elimination of mosquito breeding places is the key to an
effective and sustainable preventive strategy," the Ministry said.
The Ministry has also installed a hotline (011-267 5449) for
answering public complaints and queries.
[Byline: Bharatha Malawaraarachchi]
